  <div class="resource-body">

    <p>Assessment day can feel like a big unknown. Understanding what's going to happen — and why — makes the process less intimidating for both you and your child.</p>

    <h2>What happens during an autism assessment?</h2>
    <div class="direct-answer">
      During an autism assessment, a trained clinician observes and interacts with your child through structured play and activities, administers standardized tests, and conducts an in-depth interview with parents. The clinician is not testing whether your child can "pass" — they're building a complete picture of how your child communicates, socializes, thinks, and behaves.
    </div>

    <h2>What does the assessment session look like?</h2>
    <p>Most assessments include four components, though the exact structure varies by clinic and your child's age:</p>

    <p><strong>1. Parent intake interview (1–2 hours)</strong><br/>
    You'll be asked detailed questions about your child's development — when they first spoke, how they play, what their behavior is like at home, how they handle change, their sensory sensitivities, and your concerns. This often happens separately from your child, so the evaluator can speak openly with you. Some of this may be done via questionnaire before the appointment.</p>

    <p><strong>2. Direct observation and structured play (1–2 hours)</strong><br/>
    The evaluator will interact directly with your child using a standardized tool called the ADOS-2 (Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule, 2nd Edition). This involves a series of activities and social situations designed to elicit the kinds of behaviors that are relevant to autism diagnosis — initiating joint attention, sharing enjoyment, responding to social cues, engaging in pretend play, and more. It looks like play. It's highly structured.</p>

    <p><strong>3. Cognitive and adaptive testing (1–2 hours, if included)</strong><br/>
    Many assessments also include standardized cognitive testing (IQ-type measures) and adaptive behavior scales (how your child manages daily living tasks). These help the evaluator understand your child's overall profile — strengths, challenges, and how autism may be intersecting with other developmental factors like ADHD or language differences.</p>

    <p><strong>4. School or teacher input (collected separately)</strong><br/>
    Many evaluators send questionnaires to your child's teacher to gather observations from a different setting. Behavior in school is often different from behavior at home, and clinicians want data from both contexts.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-label">What to tell your child</span>
      For younger children, you can describe the appointment as "going to meet someone who plays games with kids." For older children, you can be more direct: "A specialist wants to learn more about how you think and learn so we can help you better." Keep it calm and matter-of-fact — your child will take cues from how you present it.
    </div>

    <h2>What tools do evaluators use?</h2>
    <p>The most common standardized tools used in autism assessments include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>ADOS-2</strong> (Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule) — direct observation, considered the "gold standard" for diagnosis</li>
      <li><strong>ADI-R</strong> (Autism Diagnostic Interview — Revised) — structured parent interview</li>
      <li><strong>Vineland Adaptive Behavior Scales</strong> — measures daily living skills and adaptive functioning</li>
      <li><strong>WISC or WPPSI</strong> — cognitive ability tests, depending on age</li>
      <li><strong>BASC or Conners</strong> — behavioral rating scales completed by parents and teachers</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Not every evaluation uses all of these. Evaluators select tools based on your child's age and the specific questions being asked.</p>

    <h2>Will my child find the assessment stressful?</h2>
    <p>It depends on your child. Many children do well because the ADOS-2 is designed to feel like play. Others find new environments, unfamiliar adults, or extended testing time challenging.</p>
    <p>Good evaluators are experienced with children who have anxiety, sensory sensitivities, and attention difficulties. They build in breaks, adapt their approach, and are skilled at working with kids who don't warm up quickly. It's worth telling the evaluator in advance about anything that typically makes your child anxious or dysregulated.</p>

    <h2>When will I get the results?</h2>
    <p>Results are usually shared in a feedback session 2–4 weeks after the assessment, once the evaluator has scored all the tests and written the report. Some clinics provide a brief verbal summary at the end of assessment day and follow up with the written report later. The written report is important — it documents all findings and recommendations and is used for school planning, insurance purposes, and future care.</p>

